"“Partition A: sealed, read-only, integrity verified. Limited derivative created before Northbridge. Partition B: sealed WSS-four incident capture, controller seal present. The partitions are separate logical evidence volumes inside one physical enclosure. Handling-event journal is separate from both.”\n\n“Can you access either partition from the display?”\n\n“No.”\n\n“Can the manual control alter them?”\n\n“No. It writes a local handling entry into the enclosure journal.”\n\n“Do not press it.”\n\n“I won’t.”\n\nPark wrote the partition states on separate lines and circled the words ONE PHYSICAL MODULE / TWO DISTINCT SEALED PARTITIONS.\n\nApex’s first written claim arrived through Mercer’s radio while she worked. An incident coordinator at Building Three requested that both electronic objects be described as “classified program media pending secure technical intake.”\n\nOrtiz listened to the wording.\n\n“Officer Park, add Apex classification and ownership claim as a separate claimant note. Do not replace the descriptions.”\n\nMercer looked at him. “That wording may expose protected architecture.”\n\n“It describes what is physically in front of my camera.”\n\n“The distinction between board and module is itself sensitive.”\n\n“Then your claimant note can say so.”\n\nOrtiz chose one MPD incident with seven object entries and seven separate packages. He did not choose Julie’s explanation of the conspiracy. He did not choose Apex’s generic noun.\n\nThe choice was smaller.\n\nIt was enough.\n\nPark arranged the empty packages on the hood in the same sequence as the worksheets. Large rigid sleeve for the case. Three smaller bags for the cartridge, log, and telematics unit. One clear property bag for the emptied folder and vehicle documents. One antistatic box for the board. One padded shielded bag for the incident module.\n\nShe wrote each prospective seal number beside the corresponding entry before removing the adhesive covers.\n\nThe sequence mattered because a bag number created before transfer could be corrected on camera. A bag number discovered after transfer could become a blank space someone filled in elsewhere.\n\nOrtiz checked both body-camera indicators. Park’s showed red. His showed red.\n\n“Dispatch, preserve continuous body-camera event from first contact through completion of interim seizure,” he said. “Cross-reference both officer IDs under the scene incident.”\n\nDispatch acknowledged.\n\nNo camera guaranteed truth. Batteries failed. Angles missed hands. Files could later be challenged. Two cameras and a dispatch instruction made an unexplained gap harder to pass off as ordinary.\n\nPark laid out seven numbered seals in order. None touched an original.\n\nThe paramedic beside Marcus said, “We are at the line.”\n\nMarcus’s left hand had begun to shake against the folder. His head came away from the frame and returned too slowly. The monitor still showed ninety-three, but the number had stopped being the only problem.\n\n“Colonel,” she said, “what city?”\n\n“Washington.”\n\n“What level?”\n\n“Six.”\n\n“What are we doing?”\n\n“Building a receipt.”\n\n“Who is receiving?”\n\nMarcus looked at Ortiz’s nameplate. “Metropolitan Police. Officer Ortiz. Interim only.”\n\nThe answers were correct. The effort required to produce them was not.\n\nOrtiz looked at the worksheets.\n\nEvery object had a description.\n\nNo transfer had occurred.\n\nThe garage clock reached 07:52:20.\n\nForward Post Arjun\n17:22:20 IST / 07:52:20 EDT\n\nThe superseding American package arrived with a valid authentication chain and no visible sign of haste.\n\nMajor Ananya Sharma distrusted it immediately for that reason and no other.\n\nThe package entered the allied terminal under a new product identifier, declared itself the current Argus reconstruction for the disputed sector, and attached the certificate path expected for an authenticated American source update. Its first operational line preserved the decision already taken on the mountain.\n\nCOUNTER-BATTERY SUPPORT: SUSPENDED\nPRIOR PROVENANCE EVENT: RETAINED\nNO EXECUTION PRODUCT ACTIVE\n\nLieutenant Sameer Qureshi read the line over her shoulder.\n\n“They have not restored the firing package.”\n\n“No.”\n\nThe guns remained safe because Sharma had ordered them safe and because the replacement did not ask for another fire mission. That part of the new product agreed with the local record.\n\nThe rest looked cleaner than the mountains had ever been.\n\nThe reconstructed picture retained weather-degraded vehicle noise on known roads, civilian communications, and broad uncertainty around the original artillery sector. It removed the impossible formation that had triggered the crisis. It also presented the disputed corridor east of Sector Zebra-Nine as operationally quiet.\n\nNo low-confidence thermal sequence.\n\nNo staggered vibration events.\n\nNo brief communications acknowledgments beneath the old carrier structure.\n\nThe area around Relay K-17 appeared not safe, not cleared, but empty of actionable anomalies.\n\nQureshi opened the prior allied product from the local cache. The earlier screen did not contain a declared K-17 threat. It did contain reference stubs attached to the raw-source review: three low-level sensor groups excluded from the artillery model, one of them tied to the K-17 maintenance approach.\n\nThe new product carried no corresponding references.\n\nQureshi compared the clock sources before saving anything. The allied terminal used the authenticated American time carried in the package. The post recorder used Indian military time. The sensor references carried their own local acquisition clocks, each offset by fractions of a second that had been documented during the morning readiness check.\n\nHe recorded those offsets rather than forcing every event into one perfect line.\n\nThe photograph of the disappearing notice had a phone time that could be challenged. The mission-abort record carried the fire-direction system’s clock. The no-fire acknowledgments came from three battery positions over a radio network with measurable transmission delay. None was identical. None needed to be.\n\n“The replacement treats the omitted events as below action threshold,” he said. “It does not mark them deleted.”\n\n“Then preserve the threshold decision.”\n\n“The product gives only the result.”\n\n“Preserve the absence of the decision too.”\n\nQureshi added a note identifying the fields the superseding package did not supply: no raw-event disposition list, no explanation for the missing K-17 reference stubs, no statement that the events had been disproved. The absence could result from an ordinary reconstruction rule, a classification boundary, or deliberate exclusion. Sharma did not choose among those possibilities.\n\nShe preserved the question they created.\n\n“Could the reconstruction have rejected them as contamination?” he asked.\n\n“Yes.”\n\n“Could the earlier product have retained false artifacts?”\n\n“Yes.”\n\n“Then which is correct?”\n\nSharma looked through the armored window. Cloud still moved across the valley. The mountain did not answer because an American certificate had arrived.\n\n“Neither becomes correct by arriving last.”\n\nQureshi brought up the local records under their own custody.\n\nHis photograph of the disappearing source-review notice.\n\nThe post’s local sensor-reference list, including the thermal, vibration, and communications event numbers that had existed before the American provenance collapse.\n\nThe mission-abort record.\n\nThe fire-direction log showing all batteries held.\n\nThe no-fire confirmation from each position, including the one loaded tube with its firing circuit safe.\n\nNone established that a team had reached K-17. None established that the new reconstruction was false. Together they established that the superseding product’s apparent completeness depended on excluding events the local post could identify by number.\n\nThe allied terminal opened a confirmation pane.\n\nSUPERSEDING PRODUCT ACCEPTED\nPRIOR ACTIONABLE PICTURE WILL BE RETIRED AT 17:24:00 IST\n\nQureshi looked at the clock. “Forty-six seconds.”\n\n“Export both product manifests to local incident storage.”\n\n“The prior package is marked for supersession.”\n\n“Supersession is not destruction.”\n\n“It may disappear from the operational display.”\n\n“Then preserve the display state, the local cache identifier, and every reference the new product does not carry.”\n\nQureshi began the export.\n\nSharma opened a new incident set and named it without accusation.\n\nCHALLENGED ALLIED RECONSTRUCTION — ARJUN\n\nShe attached the source-review photograph first, not because a photograph was stronger than an authenticated package, but because it had been created before anyone knew it would matter. The local sensor references followed. Then the abort order and no-fire record.\n\nQureshi added both American product identifiers and their certificate states.\n\nThe new package continued to look complete.\n\nThat was what completeness did when its exclusions were hidden inside a decision someone else had already made.\n\n“Major,” Qureshi said, “are you rejecting the superseding product?”\n\n“No.”\n\nHe stopped typing.\n\n“I am rejecting the assumption that authentication settles truth.”\n\nShe ordered the new product used for current allied coordination because it was the official product now available. She also ordered that no local sensor reference be discarded merely because the new package omitted it. Any future operational decision affecting the disputed corridor would require the challenged incident set beside the superseding picture.\n\nThe clock reached 17:23:58.\n\nThe prior product remained visible for two more seconds.\n\nAt 17:24:00 IST / 07:54:00 EDT, its status changed from CURRENT to SUPERSEDED.\n\nThe counter-battery suspension survived.\n\nThe K-17 anomalies did not survive inside the actionable allied picture.\n\nThey survived in Sharma’s record.\n\nCommercial Garage West of Hartwell\n07:54:00 EDT / 17:24:00 IST\n\nOrtiz did not know that anything had changed in Kashmir.\n\nHe looked at Marcus’s oxygen reading, then at the seven unfinished transfer sheets.\n\n“Ninety-three?” he asked.\n\nThe paramedic nodded. “On support. Oriented. One final entry and the handoff. Then he moves.”\n\nJulie remained where Park had placed her near the driver-side front quarter. Her right wrist had swollen against the brace. She could see every object and touch none of them.\n\n“Colonel Reed,” Ortiz said, “you may make one custody entry. Left hand. The log remains supported. If EMS stops you, the entry ends.”\n\nMarcus opened the bound log on top of the folder. Park held the folder level from beneath without taking it from his lap. The arrangement kept the paper in Marcus’s custody and removed the weight his ribs could no longer carry.\n\nOrtiz dictated the calendar date shown on the MPD worksheet into his body camera and had Marcus enter it on the next line. The prose did not matter as much as the fields.\n\nMPD incident 187463.\n\nInterim receiving officer Gabriel Ortiz, badge 4172.\n\nWitness officer Hannah Park, badge 5831.\n\nTransfer authority: Metropolitan Police seizure from a public scene under active detention.\n\nSeven separate object entries.\n\nNo final federal receiver.\n\nMarcus’s pen moved badly in his left hand. The first numbers stayed level. The last line descended toward the binding.\n\n“I transfer the listed originals to Officer Ortiz under one incident and seven separate evidence packages,” he wrote aloud as he formed the words. “I do not concede authenticity, interpretation, ownership, classification, guilt, innocence, or final jurisdiction.”\n\nOrtiz stopped him.\n\n“That last sentence is mine.”\n\nMarcus looked up.\n\nOrtiz spoke to both body cameras.\n\n“MPD receipt documents interim seizure and custody only. It does not authenticate contents, adopt any subject’s interpretation, decide classification ownership, determine guilt or innocence, or resolve final jurisdiction.”\n\nPark copied the language onto each worksheet through the carbon set. Beneath it, she repeated the common cross-reference block: Hartwell’s held challenge/access event, the WSS-4 session and local audit, PCF-27, the commercial-garage scene, and the preservation and linkage requests already carried by MPD dispatch.\n\nJulie watched Ortiz take control of the limitation rather than merely permit it. The receipt would not be the trio’s demand attached to police paperwork. It would be MPD’s description of what MPD had and had not done.\n\n“Sign if you can,” Ortiz told Marcus.\n\nMarcus signed. The name broke at the final stroke but remained recognizable.\n\nThe paramedic checked him again. “Done.”\n\n“No transfer yet,” Ortiz said. “Now.”\n\nPark removed the clear recovery-cartridge bag from the folder while Marcus kept his left hand on the folder edge. She held it inside the body-camera frame, read the serial and tamper condition, and at 07:54:48 placed it into evidence package MPD-nine-zero-one-four-four-two. She sealed the outer package without opening the inner bag.\n\nThe paper log transferred next at 07:54:56. Marcus released it only after Ortiz repeated the incident number, item description, and destination package MPD-nine-zero-one-four-four-three. Park closed the bag with the log still shut.\n\nAt 07:55:02, the dead telematics module entered MPD-nine-zero-one-four-four-four. Its original antistatic sleeve remained sealed inside the police package.\n\nAt 07:55:06, the emptied waterproof folder and the remaining PCF-27 documents entered MPD-nine-zero-one-four-four-five. Park listed the cartridge, log, and telematics unit as removed into their own packages before sealing the folder.\n\nMarcus’s left hand remained on the aluminum case handle.\n\nOrtiz crouched outside the passenger door.\n\n“Case IC-seven-seven-one-nine-four. Two latches closed. Display green. One hundred thirty-six files stated sealed, forty-seven stated incomplete, three hundred eleven stated excluded. No contents viewed. Do you transfer custody to Metropolitan Police?”\n\nMarcus looked at Julie.\n\nNot for permission.\n\nFor the fact that this was the moment six years of defended access had taught him to fear. Once he released the handle, he would have no rank, strength, or possession left to protect the record. Only the sequence.\n\n“Yes,” he said. “Interim custody to Officer Ortiz under incident one-eight-seven-four-six-three.”\n\nHe opened his hand.\n\nOrtiz and Park lifted the case together. Marcus did not help. They placed it inside a rigid transport sleeve and applied seal MPD-nine-zero-one-four-four-one across the sleeve closure, leaving both original latches and the local display visible through the inspection panel.\n\nTransfer time: 07:55:11.\n\nThe paramedic moved the stretcher closer.\n\nElias watched from the chair with the board and module held separately against his thighs.\n\nOrtiz went to him next.\n\n“Board EAT-zero-eight-eight-one-one-four-seven. Original exposed circuit board. Unconnected. Secure element visually intact. Scraped corner. Separate from module. Do you understand police are seizing it?”\n\n“Yes.”\n\n“Are you transferring it voluntarily rather than requiring me to take it from you?”\n\nElias’s fear returned in a visible tremor. “I am voluntarily transferring it to Metropolitan Police under the stated receipt. I am not admitting that I made the original deployment.”\n\n“Recorded.”\n\nPark opened a rigid antistatic evidence box. Elias placed the board inside with his left hand at 07:55:22. His bandaged right index never touched the contacts. Park closed the box and applied seal MPD-nine-zero-one-four-four-six.\n\nThe module remained.\n\nOrtiz read its physical serial, then the two partition states from the outward display.\n\n“Partition A described as sealed and read-only. Partition B described as sealed WSS-four capture. One enclosure, two distinct sealed partitions. Handling journal separate. No partition accessed. No control pressed. No connection made.”\n\nElias said, “Correct.”\n\n“Voluntary transfer?”\n\n“Yes. Same limitation. Transfer does not concede the contents mean what I believe they mean.”\n\n“Covered by the receipt.”\n\nElias released the module at 07:55:31.\n\nPark placed it in a separate padded radio-frequency-shielding bag without activating any connection or control. She left the display visible through the transparent inner window long enough for both cameras to record the partition states, then closed the outer flap and applied MPD seal nine-zero-one-four-four-seven.\n\nSeven originals or original containers.\n\nSeven entries.\n\nSeven packages.\n\nOne incident.\n\nOrtiz tore the carbonless receipt set into two subject copies. Marcus’s copy listed the five items transferred from his custody and cross-referenced Elias’s two. Elias’s copy did the reverse. Both carried the incident number, officer names, seal numbers, transfer times, and the interim-seizure limitation.\n\nPark placed Marcus’s copy beneath his left hand. She folded Elias’s and put it into his shirt pocket after asking permission.\n\nThe lead paramedic looked at Marcus’s monitor.\n\n“Ninety-three. Still oriented. We move now.”\n\nThe hard abort had approached.\n\nIt had not triggered. Marcus had not lost consciousness, become disoriented, or remained below ninety-two after oxygen support.\n\nJulie did not ask for another orientation test or another minute. The hard-abort rule had been created to prevent evidence from turning a living person into one more consumable object. Marcus was above its precise threshold only because oxygen and the paramedic’s attention were keeping him there. That was not spare time. It was borrowed medical capacity.\n\nSix years earlier, four seconds had been described as too little time to change a decision and enough time to change the official record.\n\nHere, seconds would not become an excuse to hold an ambulance.\n\n“Finish exactly what is open,” Julie said. “Nothing new.”\n\nOrtiz looked at her. “That is the plan.”\n\nIt was his plan now.\n\nMedical transport no longer waited for a better sentence.\n\n07:55:42 EDT / 17:25:42 IST\n\nThe stretcher locked beside PCF-27.\n\nMarcus tried to stand because twenty-seven years in uniform had taught his body to rise when strangers prepared to carry him. His right thigh failed before the damaged boot took a full load. The paramedics caught him under the arms and returned him to the passenger edge.\n\n“Stop helping,” the lead paramedic said.\n\n“I wasn’t.”\n\n“You were standing.”\n\n“Badly.”\n\nThey used a transfer sheet beneath him rather than make him pivot. The movement brought a hard sound from behind his teeth when his ribs compressed. Oxygen stayed in place. The monitor leads crossed his chest beneath the open coveralls. Ortiz assigned the second MPD officer at the ramp to accompany the ambulance and maintain detention without taking evidence custody.\n\nMarcus found Julie through the bodies around him.\n\n“The case?”\n\n“With Ortiz,” she said.\n\n“Receipt?”\n\n“Complete.”\n\nHe closed his eyes once.\n\nNot relief. Permission to stop holding himself upright.\n\nThe stretcher moved toward the west-gate staging area, where the ambulance could leave without crossing the Hartwell-facing side of the level. An MPD officer walked beside it. No formal charge followed Marcus down the ramp. No release did either.\n\nElias’s transport waited near the east elevator bank, separated from Marcus by PCF-27, two police officers, and the entire width of the level. EMS placed him in a wheeled chair first because his hip could not manage the stretcher height safely. Dizziness returned when they turned him. He held the receipt copy through his shirt pocket with his left hand until the chair stopped moving.\n\nOrtiz approached him one final time.\n\n“Your statement of voluntary transfer is on camera and on the receipt.”\n\n“And the board is separate.”\n\n“Seal four-four-six.”\n\n“The module?”\n\n“Four-four-seven.”\n\n“Partition A and B?”\n\n“Separately described under the module entry.”\n\nElias nodded. The answer did not protect him from arrest, prosecution, Apex, or the claim that every voluntary act proved the original lie. It gave an examiner a place to begin refusing those shortcuts.\n\nA second medical unit took him from the level under MPD detention. His board and module did not travel with him.\n\nJulie watched both routes until Park stepped into her line of sight.\n\n“Turn around.”\n\nJulie obeyed.\n\nPark checked the wrist brace again and called the injury into her camera. Standard rear-cuffing would place the right hand behind Julie’s back, rotate the damaged wrist, and require grip she did not possess. Ortiz authorized a front transport belt after the paramedic documented the restriction.\n\nPark secured Julie’s left wrist in a double-locked cuff attached to the belt. Her right forearm went into a padded medical restraint outside the brace, fixed to the other side without compressing the thumb or forcing the wrist to turn. Park checked circulation and asked Julie to report numbness beyond what was already present.\n\nThe arrangement still restrained her.\n\nIt simply did not pretend injury was defiance.\n\nPark slid a property receipt for Julie’s personal key into a separate ordinary-property envelope. It did not enter the evidence chest and did not share an item number with the originals. Julie noticed because the distinction would matter later. Evidence, property, and restrained person were three different custody problems, even when the same officer controlled all of them.\n\nOrtiz told dispatch the three medical destinations would be assigned separately and that no questioning beyond identity, medical status, and immediate safety should delay transport. He did not promise counsel, release, immunity, or a specific charge. He did not call them under arrest. He recorded detention, search, seizure, medical movement, and unresolved charging status as different acts.\n\nThat precision made the scene less dramatic to anyone listening for a confession.\n\nIt made it more dangerous to anyone depending on the acts being blurred together.\n\n\nMercer stood where MPD had kept him. The seven sealed packages were now arranged in a locked evidence transport chest beside Ortiz’s marked vehicle. The aluminum case remained visible through its sleeve panel. None had entered an Apex container. None had been handed to a federal agent. No federal agent had appeared.\n\n“Apex requests the seal list and incident number,” Mercer said.\n\nOrtiz gave him the claimant-copy reference, not a receipt transferring property.\n\n“Apex also requests immediate notification before any technical intake.”\n\n“Put it through the incident.”\n\nMercer looked at Julie. He had pursued her through Building Three, Fenwick, downtown Washington, and the garage. At the end, he had no evidence object and no authority to take one.\n\nHe did not look defeated.\n\nHe looked like a man memorizing what he would later be required to say.\n\nFrom the street below came the pulse of arriving news vehicles and the amplified instructions of officers expanding the perimeter. The first public reports would say the suspects had been captured and classified material recovered. Both facts were true in the broadest sense. Together they would sound like proof of Sterling’s story.\n\nJulie did not ask Ortiz to correct the public.\n\nThat was not the objective.\n\nPark opened the rear door of a marked MPD vehicle. Julie lowered herself carefully, unable to use the braced wrist against the frame. The transport belt kept both arms in front. The plastic seat was cold through the coveralls.\n\nBefore Ortiz closed the evidence chest, he read every seal number into his body camera and cross-referenced Hartwell, WSS-four, PCF-27, the garage scene, and the existing dispatch preservation requests under incident 187463. He stated that Hartwell’s held record, Northbridge’s local audit, commercial and traffic records, Apex directives, and any allied records remained independently controlled and were not in MPD’s physical possession merely because they had been named.\n\nThen he locked the chest.\n\n"